<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="414" type="distribution">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6870978" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6870978" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6870978/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="414" targetBox="[171,763,303,717]" targetPageId="21">
<paragraph blockId="21.[786,1378,300,722]" pageId="21" pageNumber="414">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[787,964,300,329]" pageId="21" pageNumber="414">Distribution.</emphasis>
Jalisco, México, Distrito Federal, Morelos, Tlaxcala, and Puebla, EC &amp; SC Mexico.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="414" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="21.[786,1378,300,722]" pageId="21" pageNumber="414">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[787,1036,422,447]" pageId="21" pageNumber="414">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 53-66 mm, tail 35-46 mm, ear 5-7 mm, hindfoot 12-5-14 mm; weight 5 g. The Mexican Long-tailed Shrew is medium-sized. Dorsum is dark brown, and venter is grayish brown. Tail is c.60-70% of head-body length and slightly bicolored, being dark brown above and slightly lighter below. I'
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[169,1377,728,1274]" pageId="21" pageNumber="414">has median tine located above pigmentation, and I, has two denticles, deep interdenticular space, pigmentation on one section, and long strip of pigmentation on anteromedial edge. Teeth are pigmented dark red. There are five unicuspids, third is smaller than first, second, and fourth, andfifth is significantly smaller than the rest. Teeth are pigmented dark red.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[171,1373,925,958]" pageId="21" pageNumber="414" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="21.[169,1377,728,1274]" box="[171,1373,925,958]" pageId="21" pageNumber="414">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[171,282,925,958]" pageId="21" pageNumber="414">Habitat.</emphasis>
Montane pine-oak-fir forests and tussock grasslands at elevations of ¢.2500 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
